Research Internship (Master 2)
CrowdArtifact : Modeling complex crowdsourcing processes
David Gross-Amblard (PR), Zoltàn Miklòs (MCF)  DRUID Team, IRISA Lab.

« Crowdsourcing » is a generic term for task-solving techniques that 
rely on a large group of on-line users. We can consider for example the 
success of FoldIt [1], an on-line game on protein folding, which allowed 
the crowd to solve a problem left open by specialists. Wikipedia can 
also be seen as an encyclopedia produced by crowdsourcing. Commercial 
versions of crowdsourcing also exist, such as Amazon Mecanical Turk [2]. 
In e-Science, crowdsourcing is used to gather huge data sets 
(participative sensing, for example the « Sauvage de ma rue » [4] 
project). Systems specifically designed for crowdsourcing are on their 
way (sCOOP at Stanford [5],  crowDB at Berkeley [6]). The next challenge 
for these systems is the management of complex tasks, that require 
interactions between on-line participants.

Independently, the « Business artifacts » formalism was proposed to 
model and validate complex processes. This formalism is declarative and 
data-centric and not action-centric [7,8]. The goal of this internship 
is to validate the use of business artifacts for crowdsourcing, and to 
propose relevant extensions.

The proposed roadmap is :
to understand crowdsourcing concerns, to identify its main 
implementations, economical models and interaction models.
to understand the business artifact model, with an enphasis on ActiveXML.
to propose an extension of business artifacts in order to take simple 
and complex crowdsourcing into account (without or with interactions 
between users).

This internship can be focused on its theoretical side (emphasis on 
models and formal validation of artifacts), or on its system side, with 
the implementation of a proof-of-concept. Candidates with  theoretical 
or system skills are very welcome. This proposal can be followed by a PhD.
References
[1] Foldit, solve puzzles for science. http://fold.it/portal/
[2] Amazon Mechanical turk. https://www.mturk.com/mturk/welcome
[4] Sauvages de ma rue. http://sauvagesdemarue.mnhn.fr
